revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2016-08-09 05:37:21.000000000', 'files': ['ironic/tests/unit/common/test_context.py', 'ironic/common/context.py'], 'message': 'Pass through oslo.context handled params in RequestContext

Most of the params in RequestContext.__init__() have
already been handled by oslo.context. So we don't need
to handle them one by one in ironic. We can gain many
benifits by doing thisã€‚

If we add some new properties to oslo.context, such as
"is_admin_project" in olo.context 2.6.0, we don't need
to update ironic to reflect the updates. And we can
avoid compatibility problems as well.

And also, dims has pointed out this in his comment in
the code. "roles" should be passed to __init__() instead
of setting it in ironic once the minimum version of
oslo.context is updated. "roles" was added to oslo.context
in 2.2.0, and now the minimum version is 2.4.0. So we
can do it and remove the comment now.

It is the same to the other oslo handled properties.

And BTW, we should call super.to_dict() in RequestContext.to_dict()

Change-Id: I57ffa3aadcd8f6d0f369244b8862d7423facc527
'}]
commit_message:
Pass through oslo.context handled params in RequestContext

Most of the params in RequestContext.__init__() have
already been handled by oslo.context. So we don't need
to handle them one by one in ironic. We can gain many
benifits by doing thisã€‚

If we add some new properties to oslo.context, such as
"is_admin_project" in olo.context 2.6.0, we don't need
to update ironic to reflect the updates. And we can
avoid compatibility problems as well.

And also, dims has pointed out this in his comment in
the code. "roles" should be passed to __init__() instead
of setting it in ironic once the minimum version of
oslo.context is updated. "roles" was added to oslo.context
in 2.2.0, and now the minimum version is 2.4.0. So we
can do it and remove the comment now.

It is the same to the other oslo handled properties.

And BTW, we should call super.to_dict() in RequestContext.to_dict()

Change-Id: I57ffa3aadcd8f6d0f369244b8862d7423facc527

commit_message:
Be explicit with availability zones on citycloud

The nodepool logic of picking an az if none is given is problematic on
citycloud because they have a nova-local az that we shouldn't use. Be
explicit about which zones to use.

Change-Id: I90205149c2bf0f3a68c7f7d5252567714a5e4c31

revisions:

Change the pipeline config to include invalid requirements for all
non-check pipelines so that we can keep project-pipeline configs but not
have any changes be enqueued in them. This should allow running v2 and
v3 side by side.

Add infra- versions of gate and post so that we can continue to use v3
to gate zuul, zuul-jobs, openstack-zuul-jobs and project-config.

Change-Id: I084b819ea0a4b67f36df61ccb3bfd6963cc3940d
'}]
commit_message:
Prevent non-check changes, add infra pipelines

Change the pipeline config to include invalid requirements for all
non-check pipelines so that we can keep project-pipeline configs but not
have any changes be enqueued in them. This should allow running v2 and
v3 side by side.

Add infra- versions of gate and post so that we can continue to use v3
to gate zuul, zuul-jobs, openstack-zuul-jobs and project-config.

Change-Id: I084b819ea0a4b67f36df61ccb3bfd6963cc3940d

commit_message:
Extend abort action to deploy_wait

Support using `abort` action to stop deploy_wait states and move
to deploy_fail.

`abort` action
Bump API to 1.15.

commit_message:
Switch default partition type to gpt

Systems with >2TB 'disks' are becoming more commonplace on servers
with embedded raid arrays etc. Switch default partition type to gpt
from msdos when we find ourselves with a larger disk.

Change-Id: If033412e2a5f0223bc5aeaa6cb5dd3287b6431c0
Partial-Bug: #1298362

However with zuulv3 repos won't have a remote set, they are pushed
on the server with the right branch already. So using a local
branch instead.

commit_message:
Support trusted boot using iPXE

With this patch, Ironic can boot nodes with trusted
boot using iPXE.

As iPXE didn't support multiple loading,
which is necessary to trusted boot. So trusted boot using
iPXE is actually regress to reuse PXE to deliver kernel and ramdisk.

The work flow is like this:
1. Ironic generates a special ipxe script file for nodes which
enable trusted boot.
2. These nodes boot into trusted_boot.ipxe and load pxelinux.0.
3. pxelinux.0 will directly fetch corresponding pxe config
   and load kernel and ramdisk.

It is recommended to enable trusted boot using PXE, but
if users are already using iPXE, it is still possible to
enable trusted boot for some nodes without change all to using PXE.

Implements blueprint bare-metal-trust-using-intel-txt

Change-Id: I7eb817b18a31a5b717fa33c4394fbfd51abab25a

commit_message:
[POC]Add support to boot WinPE

Many users are used to managing their machines by using WinPE.
They have many tools work well in the WinPE system which
make life easier. So why not provide the functionality in Ironic?

In this POC, Ironic simply boot a WinPE(iso) on the target host through PXE.
That's all for Ironic. Then Admin can do whatever he want by using WinPE.

Change-Id: Ic5094df0378039db7efbc5f8760e4d4673552a06

revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2017-03-13 21:22:59.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_auth/tests/tests.py', 'openstack_auth/backend.py'], 'message': "openstack_auth.backend: Error getting domain scoped token during login

Examining the Horizon Keystone driver, we see that on user login, it
will attempt to get both a domain scoped token and project scoped token.
A domain scoped token is needed since for Multi-domain deployments there
are RBAC domain-specific policy rules. However since ours is a single
domain deployment we ONLY exercise the project scoped token, and
therefore the project based RBAC rules.

There is however a bug here, where it shouldn't even be trying to get a
domain scoped token if multi-domain has been disabled in Horizon
(OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_MULTIDOMAIN_SUPPORT in local_settings)

Since this option is disabled, there is no way to assign a role for this
logon user on any domain so domain scoped token calls will always fail,
not to mention being a totally redundant call out to Keystone.

Change-Id: I311f3d1f1252c8658e778b2abad274510639a09b
Closes-Bug: #1641638
"}]
commit_message:
openstack_auth.backend: Error getting domain scoped token during login

Examining the Horizon Keystone driver, we see that on user login, it
will attempt to get both a domain scoped token and project scoped token.
A domain scoped token is needed since for Multi-domain deployments there
are RBAC domain-specific policy rules. However since ours is a single
domain deployment we ONLY exercise the project scoped token, and
therefore the project based RBAC rules.

There is however a bug here, where it shouldn't even be trying to get a
domain scoped token if multi-domain has been disabled in Horizon
(OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_MULTIDOMAIN_SUPPORT in local_settings)

Since this option is disabled, there is no way to assign a role for this
logon user on any domain so domain scoped token calls will always fail,
not to mention being a totally redundant call out to Keystone.

Change-Id: I311f3d1f1252c8658e778b2abad274510639a09b
Closes-Bug: #1641638

commit_message:
Ironic should use its own context

Currently ironic conductor use context from oslo_context directly.
The log context format string fails to get the user_name and
project_name parameter from context due to the changes to use
oslo_log. This patch aims to build the correct context structure
for ironic.

Change-Id: I0627c66957c1064d69c953f59f401739c6e4385f
Closes-bug: 1456428

commit_message:
Move to single dockerfile

Build-args will control FROM args. Centos, Ubuntu, and Debian will
remain officially supported.

This will completely remove the logic from Dockerfile and put it in the
scripts control which is the direction we have been headed for a while.

Dell EMC PS: Report total volumes on the backend

of volumes on the storage backend can be used in custom driver
filter functions.

commit_message:
Switch from ipv6-icmp to icmpv6

The firewall module changed the name of the ipv6-icmp protocol to
icmpv6[1].  This is a breaking change, but it seems that ip6tables
itself actually changed its accepted values for this at some point
so I guess we should use the new name anyway.

1: https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-firewall/commit/41fb8205b68aec8a3683e1b4f53ec9de2246d504

Change-Id: I58b5063649793af86bae360d412c3e85bb3cadd4
Closes-Bug: 1720918

Replace test.attr with decorators.attr

Function 'tempest.test.attr()' has moved to 'tempest.lib.decorators
.attr()' in Pike and will be removed in a future version[1].
This patch replaces the 'tempest.test.attr()' with the 'tempest.lib
.decorators.attr().'

[1] Iaafbb112b6eee458089cc49918359a8a8d0485e2

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2017-09-20 08:04:01.000000000', 'files': ['reference/projects.yaml'], 'message': "Adopt python-openstacksdk into shade project

While shade has been focused on a high-level python interface to
OpenStack that hides vendor differences, python-openstacksdk has been
focused on exposing the REST APIs as they are in python. The two tasks
share enough underpinnings that having two separate teams work on two
separate efforts is not an efficient use of resources these days.

python-openstacksdk by nature of its name sounds to people like it's an
official project but has never been made one which causes confusion.

As a result of shade and openstacksdk having been parallel efforts and
the different teams having slightly divergent points of view on how to
structure abstractions, openstacksdk is sadly unusable by shade in its
current form. Such divergence at this point doesn't improve the world for
anyone.

Bring the python-openstacksdk repo officially into the shade project.
The intent will be to evolve both projects into sharing a holistic
approach to consuming OpenStack APIs with openstacksdk as the lower
level and shade as a business-logic layer on top of it. This will mean
an amount of breaking changes to openstacksdk, although as it has not
yet released a 1.0 that is less bad than it otherwise could be. As
python-openstackclient uses python-openstacksdk for neutron
interactions, great care must be taken to not break
python-openstackclient in the process.

The existing shade-core will be merged with members of the
python-openstacksdk-core team who desire to continue.

Discussions of merging or consolidating repositories will follow at a
later date if they prove to be valuable but are not being proposed at
this time.

Change-Id: Ibc0e6200121a536dc7072af9049a68eac8bb28e9
"}]
commit_message:
Adopt python-openstacksdk into shade project

While shade has been focused on a high-level python interface to
OpenStack that hides vendor differences, python-openstacksdk has been
focused on exposing the REST APIs as they are in python. The two tasks
share enough underpinnings that having two separate teams work on two
separate efforts is not an efficient use of resources these days.

python-openstacksdk by nature of its name sounds to people like it's an
official project but has never been made one which causes confusion.

As a result of shade and openstacksdk having been parallel efforts and
the different teams having slightly divergent points of view on how to
structure abstractions, openstacksdk is sadly unusable by shade in its
current form. Such divergence at this point doesn't improve the world for
anyone.

Bring the python-openstacksdk repo officially into the shade project.
The intent will be to evolve both projects into sharing a holistic
approach to consuming OpenStack APIs with openstacksdk as the lower
level and shade as a business-logic layer on top of it. This will mean
an amount of breaking changes to openstacksdk, although as it has not
yet released a 1.0 that is less bad than it otherwise could be. As
python-openstackclient uses python-openstacksdk for neutron
interactions, great care must be taken to not break
python-openstackclient in the process.

The existing shade-core will be merged with members of the
python-openstacksdk-core team who desire to continue.

Discussions of merging or consolidating repositories will follow at a
later date if they prove to be valuable but are not being proposed at
this time.

Change-Id: Ibc0e6200121a536dc7072af9049a68eac8bb28e9

commit_message:
Add a spec for POST /allocations in placement

For the reasons described in the spec it would be nice to be able to
POST to /allocations to set the allocations for multiple consumers in
one request.

This spec leaves open several questions about body representation and
behavior that ought to be resolved as part of the review process.

Note that the JSON examples are handmade so may suffer from errors which
will be cleared up in the implementation

Change-Id: Ib4a3970a5d0e475c9b0a7fcb5f51e1ed3662befa
Blueprint: post-allocations

commit_message:
Properly sanitize murano package-list output before using it

In some cases, the murano package-list output may include a warning [1],
and that confuses the provider. We need to sanitize the output before
using it.

This time, we are using the right syntax for the new method.

[1] - https://review.rdoproject.org/etherpad/p/murano-failure, seen
      with urllib3 1.21.1

commit_message:
WIP: potential fix for CSV formatter encoding on py2

emit_list() inspects stdout to determine if it's been wrapped in
codecs.StreamWriter and if so passed the underlying stream & encoding to the
unicodecsv writer to avoid double encoding the output.

Change-Id: Ia4f2248a2d0fae3b047611edffa3c1773113e220
Related-bug: 1720115

subject: Make the ceph mon test more robust
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-09-06 17:52:01.000000000', 'files': ['tasks/ceph_get_mon_host.yml'], 'message': 'Make the ceph mon test more robust

The ceph mon test is currently timing out after one second,
wherever the ceph node is. We can think of cases where the
connection could be slow to establish, and a banner only appears
after a few seconds (host load for example).

We need to give more time to the ssh connection, and directly
fail if no ceph monitor was unreachable.

Change-Id: I2345dec601f7b3862e995d8e19fc15e039284147
'}]
commit_message:
Make the ceph mon test more robust

The ceph mon test is currently timing out after one second,
wherever the ceph node is. We can think of cases where the
connection could be slow to establish, and a banner only appears
after a few seconds (host load for example).

We need to give more time to the ssh connection, and directly
fail if no ceph monitor was unreachable.

Change-Id: I2345dec601f7b3862e995d8e19fc15e039284147

commit_message:
[rally] fix cases when *verify* job should be launched

Two jobs [1][2] are not required for every rally CI launch and have own
"rules" (to be executed on specific files change). There is no reason to
specify both `irrelevant-files` and `files`, since it conflicts and
makes these jobs to be launched at any change.

[1] - legacy-rally-dsvm-verify-full-create-resources
[2] - legacy-rally-dsvm-verify-full-discover-resources

Change-Id: Iff4ad381a126b078e13a6dbf711eee2976938cf9

commit_message:
Remove legacy-rally-dsvm-keystone-v2api-rally job

After turning off admin actions via keystone v2, this job lost it's
importance and doesn't check anything useful. It should be complitely
reworked to setup the correct version of OpenStack release (Pike or
Ocata) where keystone v2 exists.

Since it is redundant as for now, I see no reason to try fixing it while
process of moving to zuul v3. Let's make our gates green as a first step
and then returning to the keystone v2 job.

Change-Id: I2e7f6196f42a7e241b261ba1ac7ade84ef8c210a

commit_message:
Create static publication base job

This is for projects that need to publish something to
static.openstack.org. It publishes to
 /srv/static/{{ zuul.project.short_name }}
so that it's safe to use wherever.

There are four others that will need their own jobs since they need to
publish to somewhere other than zuul.project.short_name.

Also, fix yaml2ical publication since copy-pasta-ing from it discovered a bug.

Change-Id: Ie73bbb0c808c2e99f450dc0bbed4b0c4aa2b9fd4

subject: Move tox_envlist variable for releasenotes into job
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-10-03 02:14:32.000000000', 'files': ['playbooks/releasenotes/post.yaml', 'zuul.d/jobs.yaml'], 'message': "Move tox_envlist variable for releasenotes into job

The tox_envlist for the job that builds release note was
set in the post.yaml to fetch the tox output only.  However,
becasue it was not specified in the job, tox-siblings which
runs in the `pre` stage of `tox` would attempt to use `venv`
in the envlist field.

For jobs that do not have that venv (but do use release notes),
it would result in a failure.  This patch moves the variable out
into the job so that it's applied for the `tox-siblings` role.

Change-Id: If660822c763a973963be0c283dfdbebd97f06985
"}]
commit_message:
Move tox_envlist variable for releasenotes into job

The tox_envlist for the job that builds release note was
set in the post.yaml to fetch the tox output only.  However,
becasue it was not specified in the job, tox-siblings which
runs in the `pre` stage of `tox` would attempt to use `venv`
in the envlist field.

For jobs that do not have that venv (but do use release notes),
it would result in a failure.  This patch moves the variable out
into the job so that it's applied for the `tox-siblings` role.

Change-Id: If660822c763a973963be0c283dfdbebd97f06985

We need to correctly describe what is really happening: The dnsmasq
processes in the DHCP agent act as forwarding masquerading resolvers for
the instances in their particular subnets.

Change-Id: I50ef9f488eb1efb8f709b75537ca4a4e9efce75a
Closes-Bug: 1715842

commit_message:
Do not setup conductor in BaseAPITestCase

It's not used in any of the tests and the BaseAPITestCase has no
subclasses. This is being done to minimize any extraneous use of
eventlet driven services in the tests. In forthcoming patches,
eventlet monkey patching will be removed from the unit test tree.

Change-Id: I3d2dd128027e90a0c6f26ad2e300afc3bd6d76fe

commit_message:
Fix config option volume_backend_name's invalid overridden value

oslo.config made method set_override with enforce_type=True
by default[1], will try to convert override value according to config
option's type. Config option volume_backend_name is StrOpt[2], need
be overridden with string value.

Closes-Bug: #1681334

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/328692/
[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/cinder/tree/cinder/volume/driver.py#n66

Change-Id: If246b5fd91c7fc2c381acc56ef499ada7f411741
(cherry picked from commit 2c938e9d9e2b689184cd30709190cf8c38e8a91e)

commit_message:
Delete the default guest user from rabbitmq

Leaving the default user enabled is a security issue, as it can be used
without credentials. It also may mask issues like seen in [1].

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/1651576

commit_message:
Remove internal helper _default_security_group

_default_security_group is used only once, so this is
to remove it and to put the code logic directly in
_create_security_group_rule.

Besides, change to using filter parameter in list_security_groups
to get tenant's default security_groups, which should be equivalent
to filter result from list_security_groups(), and will make code
a bit clearer.

Change-Id: I94fdaa36624e290a03fa68563210f4521e581231

commit_message:
Update Nodepool graphite metric names

Following the update to Zuul v3 some things changed:
- nodes.delete became nodes.deleting
- nodes.used became nodes.in-use but nodes.used is still relevant
  as it's the status between 'in-use' and 'deleting'
- Add a panel for displaying failed nodes

commit_message:
Clean up repo_cmd_before command for setup-repo

Refactor the mirror setup logic to account for a few issues. We
nolonger hit https://trunk.rdoprojecg.org directly, we use our reverse
proxy.

Add error handling for an empty baseurl, and fail if missing.

Simplify nodepool variables to match /etc/ci/mirror_info.sh.

ALso, why so much copypasta? This is very error prone and should be
moved into a role in a followup patch.

Change-Id: Ia06ebad96c8db2a4eb732e80f04c72ad4c9bc6a3
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

subject: Always sleep while sending boot command
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-09-24 10:03:29.000000000', 'files': ['labs/stacktrain/core/keycodes.py'], 'message': 'Always sleep while sending boot command

Keyboard input buffer overruns are not limited to Windows batch files.
The phenomenon has been reproducibly observed on a Linux host as well.
This prevents the distro installer from coming up with error messages

Change-Id: I2ad8f437ec1ebadacc518e2c55583a5fdad75993

commit_message:
Always sleep while sending boot command

Keyboard input buffer overruns are not limited to Windows batch files.
The phenomenon has been reproducibly observed on a Linux host as well.
This prevents the distro installer from coming up with error messages
that are difficult to diagnose for users. Therefore, we enable the
delay unconditionally.

Change-Id: I2ad8f437ec1ebadacc518e2c55583a5fdad75993

commit_message:
Fix for change in virsh behavior

Some versions of virsh fail during basedisk install.

The command:
sudo virsh --connect=qemu:///system list --uuid --name --all
results in:
error: Only one argument from --table, --name and --uuid may be specified.

Observed on Ubuntu 16.04 with virsh 1.3.1.

This patch drops the "--name" option.

Change-Id: I0fbdab3539485430d4a3747fa7f3028bfe6f47ef

commit_message:
pki: conditional enablement of signing section

Only enable the [signing] section of the keystone configuration
if PKI token format is in use; other token formats don't have
support for token revocation retrieval.

Note that PKI format tokens are no longer supported >= Pike.

Change-Id: I8179ecc5d37d866588147f639ebc77a870408dfe
Closes-Bug: 1709189

commit_message:
Support network space binding of hanode relation

Rework hooks to support network space binding of the hanode
peer relation to a specific network space.

Note that the get_relation_ip function also deals with the
'prefer-ipv6' legacy configuration option handling, so it
was safe to remove some charm specific code in this area.

Change-Id: Ic69e97debddba42e3d4a140f7f9cfc95768f71c3
Closes-Bug: 1659464

commit_message:
Add shared_targets and backend_name to volumes

It would make life simpler for Nova and other consumers to know
if theyr'e dealing with devices that utilize shared targets and
give them explicit information to enable things like device
(backend) locking.

This change adds a new column to the Volume Table, shared_targets.
The shared_targets column is a boolean that indicates if the device
that hosts the volume utilizes shared_targets or not.  By default
we set this to True because it's safe to treat all volumes as shared
but not the other way around.

In addition we also transform the host column in the volumes table
and use it to add backend_name to the detailed volume response.  This
is done in the API and added as a new field in the V3 view builder
for the specified microversion.

The purpose of these two items is for Nova to easily and clearly
determine if it should utilize locking around attach/detach operations.
If shared_targets == True, then it's advisable to use locking, and the
backend_name string is a recommended lock name.

Change-Id: I406c312a1041110ede81993d775a866bd36f73d7

commit_message:
Use publish-to-pypi and friends for python releasing

We have new jobs and new project-templates for this but the migration
script borked them. Use them.

There are three templates, publish-to-pypi, publish-to-pypi-quietly and
publish-xstatic-to-pypi. publish-to-pypi-quietly is for projects that
were not doing the release announcement job.

Additionally, there were double-adds of
publish-openstack-python-tarball, including one with a dependency on
itself. Normalize those down to a single instance if it's in the job and
the job is only doing that and not one of the other publication
templates.

Change-Id: Ie8876fec55830e26ac39ccf91c9a3265604ae56b

commit_message:
scripts: install-deps.sh: Fix distribution detection

Relying on the installed package manager to detect the distribution
is not reliable since it's possible to install multiple package managers
at the same time. As such, lets simply use the information in the
os-release files.

Change-Id: I285c6cd94932f84bb9133b39d282c39d9a25b301

commit_message:
NetApp ONTAP: Fix revert-to-snapshot

In course of normal operation, the backend snapshot
name is associated with the the ID of the snapshot instance
in manila.

However, when a share is replicated or is being migrated,
the backend snapshot is not renamed. Instead, we simply
store the original name in the "provider_location" field of
the snapshot model.

Fix revert-to-snapshot methods to identify snapshots by
"provider_location"s rather than the instance IDs.

Co-Authored-By: Goutham Pacha Ravi <gouthampravi@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I4900c7aecc3da6640ea9c0d4d08012ff5b68cc58
Closes-Bug: #1694768
(cherry picked from commit bd47f93007227719e8b9eebbef9767d27025a236)

commit_message:
Remove log translations

Log messages are no longer being translated. This removes all use of
the _LE, _LI, and _LW translation markers to simplify logging and to
avoid confusion with new contributions.

See:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-i18n/2016-November/002574.html
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-March/113365.html
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Including_external_references
https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1674374

Change-Id: Idad02e61df88f9d1209757b9fbda558e117ab7b5

commit_message:
placement: avoid returning duplicated alloc_reqs when no sharing rp

This patch returns from the loop early where there are no sharing
rps, avoiding generating duplicated requests.

Change-Id: I7c73b720f09bb2371770b1c6de537bb5527785a9
Closes-Bug: #1709788

commit_message:
Add live.migration.force.complete to the legacy notification whitelist

The instance.live.migration.force.complete notificatons are missing from the
legacy notification whitelist as every test emiting them are mocked out
the rpc notifier call.

This patch adds the extra test coverage and whitelists the notifications

Change-Id: Idf20fb435a7d11ff93bcb137699a38f5e4562d4c
Closes-Bug: #1718485

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2017-09-27 16:26:05.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/functional/test_servers.py'], 'message': 'Fix race in delete allocation in ServerMovingTests

When an instance is deleted the allocation of that instance is freed
after the instance is destroyed in the db. The functional tests that
asserting resource allocation after instance delete are waiting for
the instance to disappear from the REST API. This made such tests
racy.

Fortunately the instance.delete.end notification is emitted after
the instance allocation is freed. This patch fixes the race in the
test by waiting for the instance.delete.end notification before
asserting that the allocation is freed properly.

Change-Id: I4ffd8eae73600eb2d4f6929ee6a7768adb80081d
Closes-Bug: #1719915
'}]
commit_message:
Fix race in delete allocation in ServerMovingTests

When an instance is deleted the allocation of that instance is freed
after the instance is destroyed in the db. The functional tests that
asserting resource allocation after instance delete are waiting for
the instance to disappear from the REST API. This made such tests
racy.

Fortunately the instance.delete.end notification is emitted after
the instance allocation is freed. This patch fixes the race in the
test by waiting for the instance.delete.end notification before
asserting that the allocation is freed properly.

Change-Id: I4ffd8eae73600eb2d4f6929ee6a7768adb80081d
Closes-Bug: #1719915

commit_message:
python-oneviewclient version bump

Updating the minimum version of python-oneviewclient in stable/newton.

We noticed that the CI server have been using the latest version of python-oneviewclient and
altered our jobs to use the minimum version specified at driver-requirements.
When attempting to run stable/newton with python-oneviewclient==2.0.2 we noticed
that the driver never worked with this version.

The minimum required version for stable/newton is now 2.5.1.

Closes-Bug: 1694297
Change-Id: Id396e529de3eba306421dac91e205f4b6a52573f

We incorrectly assumed that the group state will immediately become
'Pending' when a migration is requested, judging by the expected
'ErrorPending' return code of the move function.

This is not the case, as the group can be reported as 'Online' while
being on the source node, before a live migration is actually
performed successfully. This is incorrectly treated as an exception
at the moment.

This change refactors the way in which we check pending migrations.
We rely on cluster group state change events in this matter.

In case of migration timeouts, we're now attempting to cancel pending

(cherry-picked from commit e09f672e228379dbeeebad4156891ddb75a06769)

Change-Id: I6c268355213718d4d66e0e77a89c558cde3213b6
"}]
commit_message:
Fix cluster group migration status checks

We incorrectly assumed that the group state will immediately become
'Pending' when a migration is requested, judging by the expected
'ErrorPending' return code of the move function.

This is not the case, as the group can be reported as 'Online' while
being on the source node, before a live migration is actually
performed successfully. This is incorrectly treated as an exception
at the moment.

This change refactors the way in which we check pending migrations.
We rely on cluster group state change events in this matter.

In case of migration timeouts, we're now attempting to cancel pending
migrations.

Also, some of the private methods functionality is now publicly
exposed (e.g. canceling migrations, detecting queued migrations).

In the future, we're planning to implement a custom cluster resource
dll, having a finer control over this.

Conflicts:
        os_win/tests/unit/utils/compute/test_clusterutils.py
        os_win/utils/compute/clusterutils.py

(cherry-picked from commit e09f672e228379dbeeebad4156891ddb75a06769)

Closes-Bug: #1628938

Change-Id: I6c268355213718d4d66e0e77a89c558cde3213b6

commit_message:
Fix upgrades from Liberty to Mitaka

Ensure that any new configuration files are written to disk
prior to performing the package upgrade between OpenStack
releases; this ensures that the new versions of the daemons
start with the correct configuration from initial start on
package post installation configuration.

Change-Id: Ie5f3757e6c3d11fbb2d201b1f7a28e274a5f03e4
Closes-Bug: 1634923

commit_message:

commit_message:
Handle '/' in build_name for getting test_runs

According to this snippet:
http://flask.pocoo.org/snippets/76/

we can change string to path. Path type has the same behavior
as string but it allows the '/' character.

Change-Id: I7c19c7366b698d66a1cef13a822955c0da840a5a
Closes-Bug: #1720255

commit_message:
Add fluentd enable option

This change adds enable_fluentd option and enables some other log shippers
to be integrated. When enable_fluentd is "no", syslog server is also disabled.
Then, this change also adds syslog parameters to use a syslog server
prepared by users.

Change-Id: I7c83ef7fe30a6b9ab7385bcee953ad07e96b0a83
Implements: blueprint fluentd-enable-option

subject: Clean up ENV vars mistmatches in Dockerfiles
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 6598, 'name': 'Berezovsky Irena', 'email': 'irenab.dev@gmail.com', 'username': 'irenab'}, {'_account_id': 11600, 'name': 'MichaÅ‚ Dulko', 'email': 'michal.dulko@gmail.com', 'username': 'dulek'}, {'_account_id': 14352, 'name': 'Antoni Segura Puimedon', 'email': 'celebdor@gmail.com', 'username': 'toni'}, {'_account_id': 14867, 'name': 'Jaivish Kothari(janonymous)', 'email': 'janonymous.codevulture@gmail.com', 'username': 'Janonymous'}, {'_account_id': 22348, 'name': 'Zuul', 'username': 'zuul', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 23567, 'name': 'Luis Tomas Bolivar', 'email': 'ltomasbo@redhat.com', 'username': 'ltomasbo'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2017-09-20 10:59:19.000000000', 'files': ['cni_builder.Dockerfile', 'tools/build_cni_daemonset_image', 'devstack/plugin.sh', 'devstack/lib/kuryr_kubernetes', 'cni.Dockerfile'], 'message': 'Clean up ENV vars mistmatches in Dockerfiles

Containerized deployment through DevStack had two bugs related to
mismatches in handling environment variables in Dockerfiles:

1. cni.Dockerfile was using ENV vars to define CNI bin and conf
directories, but when DevStack was building them it wasn't setting them
correctly. This resulted in CNI binaries and configs ending up
in wrong directories when deploying through DevStack. This is fixed by
passing $CNI_BIN_DIR and $CNI_CONF_DIR into the build function.
2. cni_builder script used $CNI_BIN_DIR_PATH, but it was only defined in
cni.Dockerfile and was is missing from cni_builder.Dockerfile. This
resulted in malformed kuryr-cni script, that pointed to non-existing
"/kuryr-cni-bin" file. This is fixed by adding those ENV vars to
cni_builder.Dockerfile

Change-Id: I4833124231f256b74f80bd5fee732686bffab77e
Closes-Bug: 1718137
'}]
commit_message:
Clean up ENV vars mistmatches in Dockerfiles

Containerized deployment through DevStack had two bugs related to
mismatches in handling environment variables in Dockerfiles:

1. cni.Dockerfile was using ENV vars to define CNI bin and conf
directories, but when DevStack was building them it wasn't setting them
correctly. This resulted in CNI binaries and configs ending up
in wrong directories when deploying through DevStack. This is fixed by
passing $CNI_BIN_DIR and $CNI_CONF_DIR into the build function.
2. cni_builder script used $CNI_BIN_DIR_PATH, but it was only defined in
cni.Dockerfile and was is missing from cni_builder.Dockerfile. This
resulted in malformed kuryr-cni script, that pointed to non-existing
"/kuryr-cni-bin" file. This is fixed by adding those ENV vars to
cni_builder.Dockerfile

Change-Id: I4833124231f256b74f80bd5fee732686bffab77e
Closes-Bug: 1718137

commit_message:
Remove some pypy jobs that don't work

Pypy fails with "RuntimeError: cryptography 1.9 is not compatible with
PyPy < 5.3. Please upgrade PyPy to use this library." on a number of
repos, remove it from:
solum-dashboard
solum
most python-*client (swift works)
poppy
os-client-config

Also, remove those that fail pypy for other reasons:
* taskflow: Unknown PyBaseExceptionObject leads to compile errror
* python-aodhclient: Compile errors
* oslo.middleware: fails with "AttributeError: 'module' object has no
  attribute 'get_count'"

Change-Id: I6509e7df5efe3f58db872f8787ed20b72a2308c0

Please note:

       """
        An Individual Member is an ATC who has had a contribution

    requirement of 4 business days [2]

[1] https://www.openstack.org/legal/technical-committee-member-policy/

commit_message:
Set configuration parameters for the TC election

Please note:

 1. We can't use the aug-2017-elections tag as governed projects may have
    changed.  The new tag will need to be applied before 2017-10-09T23:59
 2. The dates for valid APC's is extended from the PTL election to
    include the final days of the Pike release   This matches my reading
    of the bylaws Appendix 4, Section 3.b.ii [1]
       """
        An Individual Member is an ATC who has had a contribution
        approved for inclusion in any of the official OpenStack projects
        during one of the two prior release cycles of the Core OpenStack
        Project.
       """
 3. The election period is 5 business days which exceeds the
    requirement of 4 business days [2]

[1] https://www.openstack.org/legal/technical-committee-member-policy/
[2] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/charter.html#election-for-tc-seats

Change-Id: Id8df8d4f7062316347fc5cfb3ec8323c8ec2df9c

commit_message:
Fix use of hostvars for writing provider file

The ansible hostvars variable is a dict of ansible host entries so we
need to first key off of the hostname when accessing nodepool info from
hostvars. Except that since we just want the current node's variables we
can access them directly without going through hostvars.

Change-Id: Ie6a25c8487d20189cb43c2d60afbdfd00cb5aafd

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2017-09-30 20:38:20.000000000', 'files': ['functions.sh'], 'message': 'Check for branches in zuulv3 git repos properly

Zuulv3 git repos do not have remotes. git_has_branch checks if the
branch exists in the origin remote which does not exist so all branch
specific checkouts were falling back to master which caused job
failures.

Instead just check if the base branch name exists in the repo as that
existing in a zuulv3 repo is sufficient to know we are up to date.

Depends-On: I110879bac5d8a671d73fab906ffbcf8156b1135d
Change-Id: Ifcae3ff217259926a8950f6da83212ee311002b2
'}]
commit_message:
Check for branches in zuulv3 git repos properly

Zuulv3 git repos do not have remotes. git_has_branch checks if the
branch exists in the origin remote which does not exist so all branch
specific checkouts were falling back to master which caused job
failures.

Instead just check if the base branch name exists in the repo as that
existing in a zuulv3 repo is sufficient to know we are up to date.

Depends-On: I110879bac5d8a671d73fab906ffbcf8156b1135d
Change-Id: Ifcae3ff217259926a8950f6da83212ee311002b2

commit_message:
Fix tripleo multinode job defs

This may not fix all the problems in the tripleo jobs but adds in the
base set of things we've learned about making multinode jobs work in the
migrated zuulv3 legacy jobs.

First we only run the main run playbook against the primary node.
Otherwise it runs on all the nodes and gets confused.

Second we open up the firewall between all the nodes so that they can
talk to each other.

Change-Id: Ibcba1bd338eeb7e9ccf983085838ef2a65ab647f

migrated multinode jobs.

Second only run the main run playbook against the primary test node.

commit_message:
Cleanup kolla-ansible multinode jobs

Don't know if this is sufficient to get kolla ansible multinode jobs
working but it does fix a couple items that we have discovered with the
migrated multinode jobs.

First use a base job that opens up the firewall between all tests nodes.

Second only run the main run playbook against the primary test node.
This is how it worked in v2 so running the playbook against all nodes
creates problems.

Change-Id: Iffc52b17fb0e88985364d63cd32c93c263914074

The legacy-horizon-selenium-headless job has a shell task which
attempts to use zuul-cloner to obtain the openstack/requirements

commit_message:
Add Octavia L2 member mode support

This patch introduces the modifications needed to support
L2 member mode communication between the loadbalancer and
the pool members (i.e., the pods belonging to the service).

It also includes the needed changes to set up the environment
with devstack.

Implements: blueprint octavia-layer2-member-connectivity
Change-Id: I345a71fbdf6f30f314b12aed1fc6f59177c03d00

commit_message:
Add backwards-compat playbook for /etc/nodepool/provider

The TripleO CI legacy jobs rely on the /etc/nodepool/provider file
which is no longer provided in Zuul v3.
These variables are now available directly through Ansible but we're
mostly interested in getting the existing legacy jobs working for the
time being.

Change-Id: I9e15d8c292823b3709f7ceef876c7c5bf8b6b8f5

run.yaml playbooks for multinode legacy devstack-gate jobs to the

commit_message:
Create policy.yaml sample files

oslo.policy now supports policy files in YAML (YAML is a superset
of JSON, so by definition it continues to support the legacy JSON
format). As such, provide sample policy files in YAML in addition
to the sample JSON files.

Change-Id: I39088b2a6127dd5ad0031811eb63f76213f217df
Depends-On: Ic6236665f2d55b24a56a99120ac57fc2b18e32eb

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-09-26 21:07:39.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/functional/test_servers.py'], 'message': 'Add recreate test for live migrate rollback not cleaning up dest allocs

We rollback from a failed live migration in two cases:

1. The pre_live_migration on the destination host fails. The
   _do_live_migration method calls _rollback_live_migration
   explicitly to cleanup the dest host.

2. The live migration in the virt driver fails, and the virt driver
   calls back to _rollback_live_migration in the ComputeManager.

Either way, the instance is not on the destination host, so just like
how we remove volume connections and unplug vifs from the destination
host, we need to also remove allocations for the destination node in
Placement.

This change adds a test to show that we are not currently cleaning up
allocations on the destination node when we rollback from a live
migration failure.

Change-Id: Icbd5d7ff41aa04f8f7934fdce9668762691a4a69
Related-Bug: #1715182
'}]
commit_message:
Add recreate test for live migrate rollback not cleaning up dest allocs

We rollback from a failed live migration in two cases:

1. The pre_live_migration on the destination host fails. The
   _do_live_migration method calls _rollback_live_migration
   explicitly to cleanup the dest host.

2. The live migration in the virt driver fails, and the virt driver
   calls back to _rollback_live_migration in the ComputeManager.

Either way, the instance is not on the destination host, so just like
how we remove volume connections and unplug vifs from the destination
host, we need to also remove allocations for the destination node in
Placement.

This change adds a test to show that we are not currently cleaning up
allocations on the destination node when we rollback from a live
migration failure.

Change-Id: Icbd5d7ff41aa04f8f7934fdce9668762691a4a69
Related-Bug: #1715182

revisions:
[{'number': 8, 'created': '2017-09-30 03:41:10.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/functional/regressions/test_bug_1689692.py'], 'message': 'Fix a pagination logic bug in test_bug_1689692

This test attempts to list all instances, then list them again with the
first instance as the marker and ensure that the remaining instances
are returned in the page. Now that we are doing queries to cells in
parallel, consecutive unsorted list queries can return things in
different orders as the cells may reply at different times. The fix
in this patch is to ask for results to be sorted, which is the only way
it makes sense. It worked before purely because we were always scanning
the cells linearly and in the same order.

Related-Bug: #1689692
Change-Id: I3ca2a167c902d565c36a5d5dbba1bf1c214aa20b
'}]
commit_message:
Fix a pagination logic bug in test_bug_1689692

This test attempts to list all instances, then list them again with the
first instance as the marker and ensure that the remaining instances
are returned in the page. Now that we are doing queries to cells in
parallel, consecutive unsorted list queries can return things in
different orders as the cells may reply at different times. The fix
in this patch is to ask for results to be sorted, which is the only way
it makes sense. It worked before purely because we were always scanning
the cells linearly and in the same order.

Related-Bug: #1689692
Change-Id: I3ca2a167c902d565c36a5d5dbba1bf1c214aa20b

commit_message:
Different pip install with/without venv

When testing the scripts with newer ansible version, it was failing
to install packages with pip and without venv. The reason is because
even the venv vars are set to omit, the module is still acting as it
had an empty virtualenv, causing this to fail. So just create a
different step, without the vars being set.

Change-Id: I0b268a170e69ccc36f90d875f25453d3874b22b0

commit_message:
XenAPI: upport XenServer deployment.

This contains the following chanages to support XenServer:

1. XenAPI is the virt type for XenServer, add XenAPI as the new option
for nova_compute_virt_type

2. Customize the service configuration for XenAPI

3. Create a new role for XenAPI:
In XenServer, there is a privileged domain which is known as dom0; and
it can run a number of un-privileged domains which is known as domU.
The OpenStack services run in domU. Some compute relative services
(e.g nova-compute, neutron-openvswitch-agent, ceilometer-compute) run
in a domU but need communicate with dom0 to performance some hyperviosr
operations: e.g. boot VMs; controler dom0' openvswitch; query metrics data.
https://docs.openstack.org/nova/pike/admin/configuration/hypervisor-xen-api.html

These services use XenAPI to communicate with dom0 through the
host internal management network (HIMN). When preparing the VMs where
the OpenStack compute services will run on, we can use the XenCenter's
HIMN plugin to create this network and attach the VM to this network
from XenCenter - https://github.com/citrix-openstack/xencenter-himn-plugin.

So besides the common tasks, we need some additional tasks for XenAPI:
- detect the interface connected to HIMN in domU;
- install XAPI plugins to dom0;
- install packages to dom0;
- configure iptables to allow the traffic between dom0 and OpenStack endpoits.
- etc.

The above operations will be implemented via tools belong a separate package.
But we need a new role to hold these tasks which invoke those tools. This
commit created a new role named as nova-xenapi which will be applied at early
phase so that the needed preperation work completed before other common
deployment start.

4. Add a new neutron-openvswitch-agent service:
For XenServer, we need two instances of L2Agent (neutron-openvswitch-agent
service): one manage the OpenvSwitches in domU and the other manage the
OpenvSwitches located in dom0.
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/matelakat/shared/xs-q-v1/xenserver-quantum/deployment.png

So we propose to add a new neutron-openvswitch-agent-xenapi service which
manages the ovs in dom0 for XenServer, the new service will use the same
docker image as the existing one but the ml2 configure file need to be
customized so that it can manage the remote host properly.

Change-Id: I317e39d9b2f94d96de133103154042e2ada0f43f
blueprint: xenserver-support

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-09-27 09:15:56.000000000', 'files': ['test/functional/swift_test_client.py'], 'message': "Fix functest for IPv6 endpoints

Currently the functional tests fail if the storage_url contains a quoted
IPv6 address because we try to split on ':'.

But actually we don't need to split hostname and port only in order to
combine it back together lateron. Use the standard urlparse() function
instead and work with the 'netloc' part of the URL which keeps hostname

commit_message:
Fix functest for IPv6 endpoints

Currently the functional tests fail if the storage_url contains a quoted
IPv6 address because we try to split on ':'.

But actually we don't need to split hostname and port only in order to
combine it back together lateron. Use the standard urlparse() function
instead and work with the 'netloc' part of the URL which keeps hostname
and port together.

Change-Id: I64589e5f2d6fb3cebc6768dc9e4de6264c09cbeb
Partial-Bug: 1656329

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-08-21 08:55:30.000000000', 'files': ['heat/engine/stack.py'], 'message': 'Avoid generate dependency leaves to check empty

This patch proposes to set a flag when handling leaves and check
that flag to judge if leaves is an empty set or not instead of
generating same map twice. If we have 500 edges in graph, but one
10 leaves. It makes no sense for us to go through all 500 edges

Closes-Bug: #1711539

Change-Id: I5dbc0ae18aabad7fc2ebab39f664ab3efc3a42dd
'}]
commit_message:
Avoid generate dependency leaves to check empty

This patch proposes to set a flag when handling leaves and check
that flag to judge if leaves is an empty set or not instead of
generating same map twice. If we have 500 edges in graph, but one
10 leaves. It makes no sense for us to go through all 500 edges
one extra time, just to find those 10 leaves.
Closes-Bug: #1711539

Change-Id: I5dbc0ae18aabad7fc2ebab39f664ab3efc3a42dd

subject: Fixed inconfigurable kafka consumer offset location
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2017-09-27 20:36:18.000000000', 'files': ['monasca_common/kafka/consumer.py'], 'message': 'Fixed inconfigurable kafka consumer offset location

PROBLEM: Consumer offset was resetting to the latest index rather than the earliest
SOLUTION: Modified consumer creation to include `auto_offset_reset="smallest"` which
	allows the offset to reset to the earliest known index.

NOTE: This does exactly what the whence parameter in SimpleConsumer.seek()
	is expected to do, however in order to achieve this functionality,
	the parameter `auto_offset_reset` MUST be set to either "largest"
	or "smallest".

Change-Id: I887892d80f2da9619c7f11737b3ab2e1d1dacf1e
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed inconfigurable kafka consumer offset location

PROBLEM: Consumer offset was resetting to the latest index rather than the earliest
SOLUTION: Modified consumer creation to include `auto_offset_reset="smallest"` which
	allows the offset to reset to the earliest known index.

NOTE: This does exactly what the whence parameter in SimpleConsumer.seek()
	is expected to do, however in order to achieve this functionality,
	the parameter `auto_offset_reset` MUST be set to either "largest"
	or "smallest".

Change-Id: I887892d80f2da9619c7f11737b3ab2e1d1dacf1e

commit_message:
Adds ability to disable kdump service

A puppet manifest to give the option to disable kdump service.

Security compliance frameworks have a requirement to disable
KDump. Unless the system is used for kernel development or
testing, there is little need to run the kdump service.

Change-Id: Iecf55be991d05c6300b076d67cdab4370ab4713f
Closes-Bug: #1668588
Signed-off-by: Peng Liu <pliu@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Remove wheel install complexity

I removed upper-constraints because it was redundant. With --no-index
the only wheels we can install must be in that directory, and those were
built against the upper-constraints also in that directory.

During live-migration stress testing we are seeing the following log:
Error from libvirt during undefine. Code=42 Error=Domain not found

There appears to be a race while trying to undefine the domain, and

from failing. It also matches similar error handling done for when
deleting the domain.

The next part of the bug fix is to ensure if we have any similar

commit_message:
Stop _undefine_domain erroring if domain not found

During live-migration stress testing we are seeing the following log:
Error from libvirt during undefine. Code=42 Error=Domain not found

There appears to be a race while trying to undefine the domain, and
something else is possibly also doing some kind of clean up. While this
does paper over that race, it stops otherwise completed live-migrations
from failing. It also matches similar error handling done for when
deleting the domain.

The next part of the bug fix is to ensure if we have any similar
unexpected errors during this later phase of the live-migration we don't
leave the instance stuck in the migrating state, it should move to an
ERROR state. This is covered in a follow on patch.

Partial-Bug: #1662626

Change-Id: I23ed9819061bfa436b12180110666c5b8c3e0f70

subject: Fix mocking of utcnow() for model datetime cols
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-09-15 10:58:47.000000000', 'files': ['barbican/model/models.py'], 'message': "Fix mocking of utcnow() for model datetime cols

Now when we are going to deprecate timeutils.set_time_override()
and use mock instead, it easy to hit the following gotcha: when
testr does tests discovering, it imports all modules within a given
directory and it might happen that common.db.sqlalchemy.models
is imported before timeutils.utcnow() is mocked in a test case.
In this case the SQLAlchemy model will save the reference to the
original timeutils.utcnow() function, which will be called later
when the model will be saved to a DB, if created_at or updated_at
value aren't provided.

In order to overcome this we can defer resolution of timeutils.utcnow
reference by passing lambda functions to SA Column __init__().

Change-Id: Ia05fcea6cccc8940621a0add766537e32432d245
Related-Bug: #1266962
"}]
commit_message:
Fix mocking of utcnow() for model datetime cols

Now when we are going to deprecate timeutils.set_time_override()
and use mock instead, it easy to hit the following gotcha: when
testr does tests discovering, it imports all modules within a given
directory and it might happen that common.db.sqlalchemy.models
is imported before timeutils.utcnow() is mocked in a test case.
In this case the SQLAlchemy model will save the reference to the
original timeutils.utcnow() function, which will be called later
when the model will be saved to a DB, if created_at or updated_at
value aren't provided.

In order to overcome this we can defer resolution of timeutils.utcnow
reference by passing lambda functions to SA Column __init__().

Change-Id: Ia05fcea6cccc8940621a0add766537e32432d245
Related-Bug: #1266962

commit_message:
Update ubuntu-xenial-2-node to match centos-7-2-node

In the other places subnodes is a group and there is a node called
secondary put in to it. It shouldn't matter, but as centos-7-2-node and
ubuntu-xenial-2-node are defined differently it could cause someone to
be confused or think there is a reason for the divergence.

Change-Id: Icd28da7c1c20b605841cd27f4f656e4b8f812fee

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-09-26 08:54:19.000000000', 'files': ['glance/tests/unit/v2/test_metadef_resources.py'], 'message': 'TrivialFix: Fix wrong test case

The 'md-property-create' API needs below required parameters to be
passed in the request body:
* type,
* title,
* name

If any of the parameter is absent in request body, glance-api returns
400 BadRequest with below error message:

InvalidObject(u"Provided object does not match schema 'property':
'<missing-property>' is a required property. Failed validating
'required' in schema: <API schema>
...
...
'required': ['type', 'title', 'name']

The below test case is written to validate length of name parameter
should not to be more than 255 characters:

glance.tests.unit.v2.test_metadef_resources.TestMetadefsControllers.
test_property_create_overlimit_name

This test is passing and raising HTTPBadRequest as expected but it's
not due to "name" parameter length exceeding max characters. It's
passing because this test is raising 400 error due to "type" parameter
not passed in the request body which is not the intention of this
particular unit test.

Fixed this issue by adding expected fake required attributes in
request body so that 'name' can be tested for maximum limit.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I8dd18bfff881c4ebeae65fc7c183b750f2612df6
'}]
commit_message:
TrivialFix: Fix wrong test case

The 'md-property-create' API needs below required parameters to be
passed in the request body:
* type,
* title,
* name

If any of the parameter is absent in request body, glance-api returns
400 BadRequest with below error message:

InvalidObject(u"Provided object does not match schema 'property':
'<missing-property>' is a required property. Failed validating
'required' in schema: <API schema>
...
...
'required': ['type', 'title', 'name']

The below test case is written to validate length of name parameter
should not to be more than 255 characters:

glance.tests.unit.v2.test_metadef_resources.TestMetadefsControllers.
test_property_create_overlimit_name

This test is passing and raising HTTPBadRequest as expected but it's
not due to "name" parameter length exceeding max characters. It's
passing because this test is raising 400 error due to "type" parameter
not passed in the request body which is not the intention of this
particular unit test.

Fixed this issue by adding expected fake required attributes in
request body so that 'name' can be tested for maximum limit.

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Add QoS support

This patch adds support for reading the 'enable-qos' setting from the
neutron-plugin-api relation and adding 'qos' to the extension_drivers setting
if it is True. This is part of a wider set of changes to support QoS across
the neutron charms.

The amulet tests were missing the neutron-api to neutron-gateway relation this
has been added in. A side-effect of this is that the l2-population setting is
now properly being set to True so tests were updated to expect that.

A charmhelper sync was performed to pull in the QoS update to the
NeutronAPIContext.

Note: Amulet tests will fail until the corresponding neutron-api change
lands

Depends-On: I1beba9bebdb7766fd95d47bf13b6f4ad86e762b5
Change-Id: I6dc71a96b635600b7e528a9acdfd4dc0eded9259
Partial-Bug: #1705358

commit_message:
Put searchlight into maintenance mode

Searchlight is a mature technology.  The current project team still
maintains it and it is used by members of the team.
However, there is no longer anyone working full time on Searchlight.

That being said, expansion of Searchlight relies on plugins for those
projects wishing to be indexed by the service.  The design and
architecture of plugins is well-documented and the plugins can be
stored in the appropriate project's repository.  Thus development of
Searchlight's functionality can continue even while the project itself
is in maintenance mode.

The project has a current PTL, so the liason requirements for the tag
are met.

Change-Id: Iefb735d3e3b651a9f9d2231dd730ca2bddc296ea

revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2017-09-20 10:41:17.000000000', 'files': ['reference/projects.yaml'], 'message': 'Cyborg Application For Official Projects

First of all thanks for TC audience for our project update at PTG.
The overview slide presented at the meeting could be found here[0].

**What is Cyborg**
Cyborg is a new project that aims to provide a general management
framework for accelerators[1], such as FPGA, GPU, ARM SoCs, NVMe
SSDs,DPDK/SPDK,eBPF/XDP and so forth, basically any types of dedicated
hardware/software that designed specifically to accelerate the
performance of the general computing infrastructure.

**Motivation**
The motivation behind Cyborg projects orginally came from NFV in Telco,
and later on more from Scientific WG on HPC and public cloud providers
who want to provide FPGA/GPU instances. Details of the requirement for
Cyborg could be found in the slide[0]

**Two Important Facts**
- Cyborg is started from scratch within the community, which means there
was no code dump from vendor and we wrote every specs and code implement-
ation from zero in an OpenStack way.
- Every decision in Cyborg project is done through election/voting, even
the project name was voted from team members.

**One More Fun Fact**
* We have the LONGEST team meeting in OpenStack (meeting starts late in
China timezone and often left open since the organizer passed out on desk,
we are working hard to improve on that :) )

**Functionality**
Cyborg's two main jobs are resource discovery and life cycle management,
which means Cyborg leaves the functionality of scheduling entirely to
Nova when the user needs a virtual machine deployment, or Kubernetes/Mesos
/Docker if the user needs container solution running on baremetal.

**Cross Projects Relationship**
As mentioned above, Cyborg interacts with Nova via Placement. Cyborg does
not reinvent any wheels or tries to drop in to replace any current modules.
It heavily relies on working with the current OpenStack structure. Nova's
FPGA/GPU support is very critical for Cyborg to be able to work for VM
related deployments.

In short, after cyborg-agent performed resource discovery operation via
various drivers it connects to, it reports the accelerator resource info
to Placement. Placement will then provide an aggregate view of both general
and accelerator resource for Nova scheduler. When Nova successfully spawn
an instance on a compute node with accelerator, nova will notify cyborg and
cyborg-api will notify cyborg-db to change the resource status from
"available" to "in use", similar to the Nova-Cinder interaction for volume.

Cyborg has constant discussion with the Nova/Placement team and
we will continue to do so in Queens and following cycles to make sure we got
an awesome collaboration.

Cyborg has also very good relationship with the Scientific WG and OPNFV
DPACC project. We gathered inputs/requirements from these groups.

**Scenario/Usage**
To put it very simply, if you have just one type of accelerator, you could
just use what Nova provides for PCI-passthrough functionalities. If you have
more than one types of accelerators, or you have one type of accelerator but
you want fine grained control, then you probably needs Cyborg on the side to
help you manage them, working alongside Nova.

**Community Principle Compliance**
Cyborg project follows the core principle of "Four Opens" within OpenStack
Community:

* Open Source
This goes without saying, all the Cyborg source code could be found at
OpenStack repo[2] or its github mirror[3], including feature codes,
documentations[4] and tests[5]. Apache Lisence 2.0 is applied as usual.

* Open Design
As mentioned above, Cyborg is designed from ground up within the community.
We have weekly team meetings[6] at #openstack-cyborg and public available/
searchable meeting logs[7]. We have organized PTG design sessions for each
of the past ones[8][9]. We have also used [acceleration] or [cyborg] for
mailinglist discussion.

* Open Community
Cyborg has a truely diverse team composition with no single vendor
dominance[10]. PTL of Cyborg comes from Huawei and current two core reviewers
come from RedHat and Lenovo. We have also gone through election/voting for
these positions[11][12].

* Open Development
All of the Cyborg pacthes could be found here[13]. We have a implicit policy
of the core that landed the patch should comes from a different company of the
ones that submit the patches. We try to review the patches as thorough as
possible and we are honored to have people from other team help reviewing,
for example[14][15]. Cyborg team also tries to utilize all the available
community infrastructure, e.g CI/CD[16]

The Cyborg project team has been doing everything according to the community's
tradition and best practices. Although it is far from perfect, we believe it is
on the right track. We also believe that by putting Cyborg under official
governance, it will show OpenStack's capability on heterogeneous computing that
provides the foundation for AI, Machine Learning, HPC, NFV and many other
cutting-edge technologies.

0. https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1RyDDVMBsQndN-Qo_JInnHaj_oCY6zwT_3ky_gk1nJMo/edit?usp=sharing
1. https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Cyborg
2. https://review.openstack.org/gitweb?p=openstack/cyborg.git;a=summary
3. https://github.com/openstack/cyborg
4. https://github.com/openstack/cyborg/tree/master/doc/source
5. https://github.com/openstack/cyborg/tree/master/cyborg/tests
6. https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/CyborgTeamMeeting
7. https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Cyborg/MeetingLogs
8. https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/cyborg-ptg-pike
9. https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/cyborg-queens-ptg
10. http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=openstack-others&module=cyborg&metric=person-day&release=all
11. https://openstack.nimeyo.com/113991/openstack-cyborg-nominate-rushil-justin-kilpatrick-reviewers
12. https://openstack.nimeyo.com/117806/openstack-dev-cyborg-queens-ptl-candidacy?show=117812
13. https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:openstack/cyborg

Change-Id: If0679c80f72f48cbe5fbc50c0a182661e97793fe
Signed-off-by: zhipengh <huangzhipeng@huawei.com>
'}]

subject: Add missing required-projects for TripleO jobs using devstack-gate
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2017-09-29 16:35:29.000000000', 'files': ['zuul.d/zuul-legacy-jobs.yaml'], 'message': 'Add missing required-projects for TripleO jobs using devstack-gate

A lot of TripleO jobs leverage devstack-gate and as such needs a
batch of required-projects, otherwise devstack-gate fails to retrieve
the projects when it bootstraps $PROJECTS.

Change-Id: I9cdc182ac5800e1566c04e6f21e454956d82ad33
'}]
commit_message:
Add missing required-projects for TripleO jobs using devstack-gate

A lot of TripleO jobs leverage devstack-gate and as such needs a
batch of required-projects, otherwise devstack-gate fails to retrieve
the projects when it bootstraps $PROJECTS.

Change-Id: I9cdc182ac5800e1566c04e6f21e454956d82ad33

commit_message:
Update legacy post playbooks to pull from primary

This should be a no-op for single-node jobs, but for multi-node jobs it
should keep them from trying to copy logs from all of their nodes,
which they are not designed to do.

Change-Id: Ibcf158f1b8082fbffeb48fa48c6592c87e056d01

subject: Create legacy nodesets and switch all legacy jobs
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2017-09-29 16:35:16.000000000', 'files': ['zuul.d/zuul-legacy-jobs.yaml', 'zuul.d/nodesets.yaml', 'zuul.d/jobs.yaml'], 'message': 'Create legacy nodesets and switch all legacy jobs

The legacy jobs were designed to pull logs only from their 'primary'
node. The converted jobs are pulling them from all of the nodes.

Create legacy- versions of all the nodeset that name the single node
"primary". Update all of the legacy jobs to use these. The next patch
will update all of the post playbooks to be hosts: primary.

Legacy versions of multi-node nodesets aren't strictly needed as the
non-legacy versions already have a 'primary' ... but it makes both
global search and replace as well as migration docs simpler.

Change-Id: Ic04f38d9b5251f5a1a5426f890728bf0dd9b4e9c
'}]
commit_message:
Create legacy nodesets and switch all legacy jobs

The legacy jobs were designed to pull logs only from their 'primary'
node. The converted jobs are pulling them from all of the nodes.

Create legacy- versions of all the nodeset that name the single node
"primary". Update all of the legacy jobs to use these. The next patch
will update all of the post playbooks to be hosts: primary.

Legacy versions of multi-node nodesets aren't strictly needed as the
non-legacy versions already have a 'primary' ... but it makes both
global search and replace as well as migration docs simpler.

Change-Id: Ic04f38d9b5251f5a1a5426f890728bf0dd9b4e9c

commit_message:
Transfer snapshots with volumes

This feature will change Cinder to transfer
snapshots with volumes at the same time by default.
If user don't want transfer snapshots, they could use
optional argument '--no-snapshots'.

APIImpact
Add an optional argument '--no-snapshots' in transfer API.

Change-Id: I287209404a31df91586bbe6bb86daed5c9a7f884
Implements: blueprint transfer-snps-with-vols

commit_message:
Disable merge-check pipeline

* It uses merger resources, and Gerrit shows up merge conflicts now.
* It performs speculative configuration on changes with config
  updates, which is expensive.
* In some cases, it can race with reconfigurations to report false
  failures on config changes.

Change-Id: Ic5bbc60e6a0aa19799a903fd5ada7bbe3846bf90

commit_message:
WSGI configuration missing directive

WSGI configuration is missing the directive
"WSGIApplicationGroup %{GLOBAL}" after
WSGIProcessGroup" in the horizon template.
Of all WSGI configuration templates it is
the only one that does not have the
"WSGIApplicationGroup" line.

Change-Id: I26d4f78becf369693754c8a8e72a31060127ce41
Closes-Bug: #1717922

in ocata, so these jobs wouldn't work.

filter:

commit_message:
Add QoS support

This patch adds support for reading the 'enable-qos' setting from the
neutron-plugin-api relation and adding 'qos' to the extension_drivers setting
if it is True. This is part of a wider set of changes to support QoS across the
neutron charms.

A charmhelper sync was performed to pull in the QoS update to the
NeutronAPIContext.

Note: Amulet tests will fail until the corresponding neutron-api change
lands

Depends-On: I1beba9bebdb7766fd95d47bf13b6f4ad86e762b5
Change-Id: I9d857a4f2a25c6080963a0f3f6e6592c0a77d133
Partial-Bug: #1705358

Adding database drop jobs

on deletion of Helm chart. This job is configurable to be enabled or
disabled in the values.yaml file for each chart.

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-05-13 16:39:23.000000000', 'files': ['tempest/api/network/admin/test_agent_management.py'], 'message': "Remove Neutron agent management API tests

The Neutron community has been engaged in a long running
effort to move some of the networking API tests to the Neutron
tree. We started by copying the api/network directory tree,
later keeping only the tests, importing the test infrastructure
from Tempest. We continued by minimizing the imports we do
from Tempest (/tempest.lib) directly, and introduced a Neutron
Tempest plugin.

One issue that remains is that the tests are still duplicated.
Since the tests run against stable/{kilo|liberty|mitaka} and
master, it should be safe to dedup. The Neutron community drew
a line in the sand, where core resources remain to be tested
in Tempest and more 'advanced' APIs are tested in Neutron.
More detail may be found here:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/neutron/devref/
development.environment.html#api-tests

I removed all API tests for 'core resources' from the Neutron
tree, I propose that we remove the inverse from Tempest.
The full list of tests that I propose be removed from Tempest
is tracked here:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/neutron-tempest-defork
Ctrl-F for 'Tests that should be deleted from Tempest'

I believe that as far as Tempest test removal criteria found at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/QA/Tempest-test-removal
This case falls under the first exception:
'The class of testing has been decided to be outside the scope of tempest'
and we may skip the three prong rule for removal. Note that none of the
tests I'm proposing for removal are a part of refstack.

Change-Id: Ibcf188d2256683597b6368f047ebf8c8aa1a2ee5
Related-Bug: #1552960
"}]
commit_message:
Remove Neutron agent management API tests

The Neutron community has been engaged in a long running
effort to move some of the networking API tests to the Neutron
tree. We started by copying the api/network directory tree,
later keeping only the tests, importing the test infrastructure
from Tempest. We continued by minimizing the imports we do
from Tempest (/tempest.lib) directly, and introduced a Neutron
Tempest plugin.

One issue that remains is that the tests are still duplicated.
Since the tests run against stable/{kilo|liberty|mitaka} and
master, it should be safe to dedup. The Neutron community drew
a line in the sand, where core resources remain to be tested
in Tempest and more 'advanced' APIs are tested in Neutron.
More detail may be found here:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/neutron/devref/
development.environment.html#api-tests

I removed all API tests for 'core resources' from the Neutron
tree, I propose that we remove the inverse from Tempest.
The full list of tests that I propose be removed from Tempest
is tracked here:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/neutron-tempest-defork
Ctrl-F for 'Tests that should be deleted from Tempest'

I believe that as far as Tempest test removal criteria found at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/QA/Tempest-test-removal
This case falls under the first exception:
'The class of testing has been decided to be outside the scope of tempest'
and we may skip the three prong rule for removal. Note that none of the
tests I'm proposing for removal are a part of refstack.

Change-Id: Ibcf188d2256683597b6368f047ebf8c8aa1a2ee5
Related-Bug: #1552960

commit_message:
Fix api-ref for reset group snapshot

reset-group-snalshot api-ref not correct for 'status' attribute.
That is mentioned as optional for request.
'status' in API request is mandatory attribute.

Also 'project_id' is mentioned as body element instead of path.

Those are confusing while implementing tests for this API
 - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/495735/
https://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/block-storage/v3/#reset-group-snapshot-status
Closes-Bug: #1719930

Change-Id: Id2016f86d0eae60d96df7a12eda1bbec9d1129a8

commit_message:
Fix a migration issue of Huawei driver

While migrating volume crossing backends by the host-based way,
after data copying is done, Huawei driver's update_migrated_volume
method doesn't return the provider_location property, which
results old and new volumes' provider_locations aren't swapped as
expected, afterwards, while deleting the old volume, new volume's
provider_location will be used and the if-volume-exist-check fails
because it verifies the new volume's LUN ID actually on the old
backend, which certainly doesn't exist.

This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: Iee27c0368522c90525a4b8ad757f9fb89dc293a0
(cherry picked from commit 011daa9b463043a15f9e97986ecce6233ac72de5)

subject: Correct RBD Provision stats&fix a perf problem
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2017-09-29 09:08:50.000000000', 'files': ['cinder/volume/drivers/rbd.py'], 'message': 'Correct RBD Provision stats&fix a perf problem

Use v.size() to get virtual size of volumes for
provisioned_capacity_gb instead of v.diff_iterate().
There are two reasons:

1.The diff_iterate() API of librbd returns actually
allocated size of volumes, but cinder-scheduler just want
virtual size by v.size() for provisioned_capacity_gb to
compute the ratio of over subscription.

2.Traverse all the volumes with diff_iterate() brings
greater pressure to both cinder and ceph cluster. It
can cause critical problems:
a. Run a periodic task may need a long time(may be need
serval minutes), depend on how many volumes in backend
pool and the load of ceph cluster;
b. Periodic report of the service can be blocked, and
cause service down in the end.

Change-Id: If37e3820ebd00c85e11f1fbb1f32faabf0890bbb
Closes-Bug: #1649956
(cherry picked from commit b907450d7d7500fbcb9e4040efc2d0e42f4a78f9)
'}]
commit_message:
Correct RBD Provision stats&fix a perf problem

Use v.size() to get virtual size of volumes for
provisioned_capacity_gb instead of v.diff_iterate().
There are two reasons:

1.The diff_iterate() API of librbd returns actually
allocated size of volumes, but cinder-scheduler just want
virtual size by v.size() for provisioned_capacity_gb to
compute the ratio of over subscription.

2.Traverse all the volumes with diff_iterate() brings
greater pressure to both cinder and ceph cluster. It
can cause critical problems:
a. Run a periodic task may need a long time(may be need
serval minutes), depend on how many volumes in backend
pool and the load of ceph cluster;
b. Periodic report of the service can be blocked, and
cause service down in the end.

Change-Id: If37e3820ebd00c85e11f1fbb1f32faabf0890bbb
Closes-Bug: #1649956
(cherry picked from commit b907450d7d7500fbcb9e4040efc2d0e42f4a78f9)

commit_message:
Correct RBD Provision stats&fix a perf problem

Use v.size() to get virtual size of volumes for
provisioned_capacity_gb instead of v.diff_iterate().
There are two reasons:

1.The diff_iterate() API of librbd returns actually
allocated size of volumes, but cinder-scheduler just want
virtual size by v.size() for provisioned_capacity_gb to
compute the ratio of over subscription.

2.Traverse all the volumes with diff_iterate() brings
greater pressure to both cinder and ceph cluster. It
can cause critical problems:
a. Run a periodic task may need a long time(may be need
serval minutes), depend on how many volumes in backend
pool and the load of ceph cluster;
b. Periodic report of the service can be blocked, and
cause service down in the end.

Change-Id: If37e3820ebd00c85e11f1fbb1f32faabf0890bbb
Closes-Bug: #1649956

commit_message:
Add meta attribute support to stonith manifests

Stonith devices can also take a 'meta' attributes that
describes further characteristics of their behaviour.
We add a 'meta_attr' parameter that can be used to specify
additional meta parameters when invoking pcs.

Note: fence_xvm was done by hand as it is not autogenerated.

Tested with the upcoming fence_compute manifest (autogenerated)
and meta attributes are correctly set when meta_attr is not
undef:
$ pcs stonith show stonith-fence_compute-fence-nova |grep Meta
  Meta Attrs: provides=unfencing

Change-Id: I3648b358ca9799c2a430878ca5b17f570914a06d

commit_message:
Retry container creation in swift

Because of cache management container creation in Swift is somewhat
racy, as we create containers lazily. Work around that issue by retrying
creation a few times.

Change-Id: I4c3671cdb23df1597c2b5c9c581ad7225847d64d
Closes-Bug: #1719525
(cherry picked from commit b010ba13ebe90826c89f8fa2a5227eb03c69e205)

commit_message:
Temporarily pin cliff to 2.8.0 in tempest virtualenv

When installing tempest from source we are getting cliff-2.9.0
in the virtualenv. This version of cliff requires that all tempest
plugins have a top_level.txt in the egg-info [1] which is not
present in some RDO packages.

We are fixing this in RDO but it will take a while to fix the
macro, rebuild the packages and get a new puppet promotion
(which currently is blocked by other cinder issue), so I'm
proposing to temporarily pin back to cliff 2.8.0 until RDO
repos are ready for it.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/501863/

Change-Id: I9c91a316b2f8acaa1f4b0882f0799f90e11464d9
